Sadtu says none of its members will be returning to schools that haven't met COVID-19 safety requirements. Most schools have been reported to have no or insufficient personal protective gear. Courtesy #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - The South African Democratic Teachers Union (Sadtu) says none of its members will be returning to schools that haven't met COVID-19 safety requirements. Most schools have been reported to have no or insufficient personal protective gear. READ: SAHRC asks Motshekga to reconsider schools reopening Sadtu General-Secretary Mugwena Maluleke says unions and governing body associations met with Minister of Basic Education, Angie Motshekga. Maluleke said the system will not be ready for teachers and pupils to go back to school on Monday. “When it comes to the learners, our position is we don't want a staggered approach. We need to make sure the system is perfect. The teacher have been trained, they've been oriented...” Maluleke added. Reopening of schools: Dates announced for other grades Grade 7 and 12 pupils are expected to start on Monday. READ: Schools are not ready to reopen in June - Sadtu Meanwhile, Motshekga is set to address the nation of the state of readiness in school on Sunday evening. - Coronavirus Hotline Number: 0800 029 999 from 8 am to 4 pm, Monday to Friday. Help protect your loved ones by sharing this official South African government COVID-19 service with your family, friends and community. Send HI to 0600 123 456 on WhatsApp. The NICD has another Clinician Hotline to improve #COVID19 communication and support for healthcare providers. The Clinician Hotline is 0800 11 1131, operating 24 hrs. The Public Hotline is 0800 029 999 also operating 24hrs.